Patch Set 2:

> Do you mind to contribute that split?

To be honest, I'd rather spend my time on other fixes.

> I did not get the idea how that helps. I hope to understand it when i see the result. somehow both have to link each other?

It helps because there are different targets/readers.
End-users don't care about extension points and so on, and showing technical details to them diminishes their understanding and the impact of the message. Those are targetted by the platform.html document.
Plugin developers want to be aware of new APIs and Platform capabilities that they can enable in their products. They want details like extension-point ids, new classes and so on. Those read the platform_isv.html document.
You can see the entries about multiple carets or code mining for example of how API and user oriented changes are described in different documents.

Patch Set 2: Verified+1 Code-Review+1

As long as nobody wants to do the split, I suggest to merge it. Would be nice to split the docu but some docu is better than no docu.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Sorry to sound negative, but it is vital for the sustainability of the project that committers embrace the rules and habits that have allowed the project to remain successful. We can change the rules and habits, but this is to discuss on other places first.
And overall API quality, documentation and many other things are part of the sustainability and success. I know it can be boring but it is important and as project leads, I don't think we should lower the quality bar, particularly with people who are already elected as committers and then are now also responsible for the continued quality of the project.

And sure, quality has an extra cost, but someone who is not ready to pay the extra cost for quality that is required for the project to be sustainable should really consider whether they're a good fit for the project as committers or not.
We can be more tolerant with contributors, but when people are committers, they should just commit to complete the work according to quality standard without telling other committers to finish their work for them.

So Jorg, I hope -and I actually know- that you can reach the expectation (and pressure) we put on committers when it comes to quality and can finish what you've started by considering the requested changes. It's in the best interest of the project.
